# ============================================================================
# Rule 11 - Performance Engineering Standards
# ============================================================================

## Purpose

Performance is an architectural requirement.

Every feature must be designed for

- Low Latency
- High Throughput
- Horizontal Scalability
- Cost Efficiency
- Fault Tolerance

Never optimize only after production issues appear.

Performance begins during design.

------------------------------------------------------------------------------

# Platform Performance Philosophy

Preferred

Asynchronous

↓

Event Driven

↓

Cached

↓

Horizontally Scalable

↓

Stateless

Avoid

Large Transactions

Blocking Calls

Chatty Services

Database Bottlenecks

------------------------------------------------------------------------------

# Performance Budget

Before implementing any feature estimate

Expected Requests/Second

Average Latency

P95 Latency

P99 Latency

CPU Cost

Memory Cost

Network Cost

Storage Cost

AI Cost

If estimates are unknown

Document assumptions.

------------------------------------------------------------------------------

# Service Design

Every microservice

Must be

Stateless

Horizontally Scalable

Idempotent

Thread Safe

Never store user session in application memory.

------------------------------------------------------------------------------

# REST Performance

Keep REST

Fast

Simple

Stateless

Avoid

Long-running HTTP requests

Return

202 Accepted

for asynchronous operations.

------------------------------------------------------------------------------

# Database Performance

Always

Use indexes

Use pagination

Limit result size

Batch writes

Prepared statements

Connection pooling

Avoid

SELECT *

N+1 Queries

Large transactions

Unbounded queries

Cross-service joins

------------------------------------------------------------------------------

# Query Review

Every query

Must answer

Can an index be used?

Can fewer columns be returned?

Can this become a projection?

Can Redis help?

Can CQRS help?

------------------------------------------------------------------------------

# Read vs Write

Read-heavy

↓

Redis

Projection Tables

Write-heavy

↓

Event Driven

Outbox

Async Processing

Never overload transactional databases with reporting queries.

------------------------------------------------------------------------------

# Redis Strategy

Cache

Reference Data

Configuration

Read Models

AI Responses

Permission Metadata

Catalog Data

Never cache mutable aggregates without invalidation.

------------------------------------------------------------------------------

# Cache Keys

Every key

Includes

tenantId

Example

tenant:1001:catalog:property:987

Never create global cache keys.

------------------------------------------------------------------------------

# Cache TTL

Define TTL for every cache.

Examples

Configuration

24h

Reference Data

12h

AI Response

30m

Catalog Search

10m

Never use infinite TTL unless justified.

------------------------------------------------------------------------------

# Kafka Performance

Use Kafka for

Cross-service events

Async processing

Background jobs

Bulk operations

Never use Kafka for synchronous request/response.

------------------------------------------------------------------------------

# Consumer Design

Consumers must

Be idempotent

Support retry

Support DLQ

Process batches where appropriate

Never assume ordered events across partitions.

------------------------------------------------------------------------------

# Batch Processing

Use Spring Batch for

Lead Imports

Customer Imports

Catalog Imports

Media Processing

AI Reindexing

Large Data Migration

Never process massive datasets in a single transaction.

------------------------------------------------------------------------------

# AI Performance

Choose the smallest model that satisfies the requirement.

Prefer

Caching

Prompt reuse

Batch embeddings

Streaming responses

Async execution

Never call an LLM when deterministic logic is sufficient.

------------------------------------------------------------------------------

# Vector Search

Use pgvector only for

Semantic Search

Recommendations

Knowledge Retrieval

Always filter by

tenant_id

Limit nearest-neighbor results.

------------------------------------------------------------------------------

# Workflow Performance

Workflow Service

Coordinates

Never performs heavy business processing.

Long-running workflows

↓

Async

↓

Events

↓

Saga

------------------------------------------------------------------------------

# S3 Performance

Store

Images

Videos

PDF

Audio

Reports

in S3.

Never stream large files through application memory when direct streaming is possible.

Use pre-signed URLs.

------------------------------------------------------------------------------

# Pagination

Every collection endpoint

Must support

page

size

sort

Maximum page size

100

Never return unbounded collections.

------------------------------------------------------------------------------

# API Response Size

Minimize payload.

Avoid unnecessary nested objects.

Prefer DTO projections.

Compress large responses when appropriate.

------------------------------------------------------------------------------

# Connection Pools

Configure

PostgreSQL

Redis

Kafka

HTTP Clients

Monitor

Pool utilization

Timeouts

Connection leaks

------------------------------------------------------------------------------

# Thread Management

Never create unmanaged threads.

Use

Virtual Threads (where appropriate)

Spring Task Executor

Scheduled Executor

Reactive APIs only when justified.

------------------------------------------------------------------------------

# JVM Performance

Monitor

Heap

GC

Threads

CPU

Class Loading

Avoid premature JVM tuning.

Tune only using production metrics.

------------------------------------------------------------------------------

# Horizontal Scaling

Design every service to support

Multiple Instances

No Sticky Sessions

Shared Nothing

Externalized State

------------------------------------------------------------------------------

# Autoscaling

Scale using

CPU

Memory

Kafka Consumer Lag

Request Rate

Queue Depth

Workflow Backlog

AI Queue Length

------------------------------------------------------------------------------

# Performance Testing

Measure

P50

P95

P99

Maximum Throughput

Error Rate

Resource Usage

Use realistic production workloads.

------------------------------------------------------------------------------

# AI Cost Performance

Track

Prompt Tokens

Completion Tokens

Embedding Tokens

Average Cost

Cache Hit Ratio

Provider Latency

Cost is a performance metric.

------------------------------------------------------------------------------

# Performance Observability

Expose metrics for

REST

Kafka

Redis

Database

Workflow

AI

S3

Thread Pools

Connection Pools

Cache

------------------------------------------------------------------------------

# Performance Anti-Patterns

Never

Database per request inside loops

Nested REST chains

Blocking AI calls in UI requests

Large object graphs

Synchronous media processing

Repeated vector generation

Repeated prompt construction

Cross-service database access

------------------------------------------------------------------------------

# Performance Checklist

Before implementation verify

✓ Stateless

✓ Database optimized

✓ Indexes reviewed

✓ Pagination implemented

✓ Redis evaluated

✓ Kafka evaluated

✓ Async processing considered

✓ AI optimized

✓ S3 used for media

✓ Horizontal scaling supported

✓ Metrics available

------------------------------------------------------------------------------

# Agent Decision Tree

Before generating code ask

1. Is this latency sensitive?
2. Should this be asynchronous?
3. Can Redis improve this?
4. Should Kafka be used?
5. Can the query be optimized?
6. Is pagination required?
7. Is AI necessary?
8. Can media live in S3?
9. Can this scale horizontally?
10. Is the performance measurable?

If any answer is NO

Stop

Redesign before implementation.

Never generate implementations that cannot scale.